193
00:10:54,761 --> 00:10:56,022
that we learned in our first year,

194
00:10:57,283 --> 00:11:01,227
was that we didn't expect folks who have caused harassment

195
00:11:01,687 --> 00:11:05,950
or harm in the industry to text us for support.

196
00:11:06,691 --> 00:11:13,955
But it actually really the first week that we opened started happening just kind of on its own.

197
00:11:15,335 --> 00:11:19,918
And that was a moment for us. We had to really look at, you know, what is

198
00:11:20,738 --> 00:11:23,559
the space that we're creating? What are we doing this work for?

199
00:11:25,580 --> 00:11:29,103
A lot of other hotline models, a lot of rape crisis hotlines, for example,

200
00:11:29,824 --> 00:11:36,089
will not offer services to folks who have been accused of or have like

201
00:11:36,649 --> 00:11:39,391
protective orders against them for sexual violence.

202
00:11:40,832 --> 00:11:43,776
And so, yeah, we really had to ask ourselves, like, what do we want to do?

203
00:11:43,796 --> 00:11:45,097
Do we want to hang up on these people?

204
00:11:45,117 --> 00:11:49,542
Do we want to talk to them, even though they're kind of causing the harassment

205
00:11:49,563 --> 00:11:51,064
and we're an anti-harassment resource?

206
00:11:51,605 --> 00:11:54,969
And ultimately, we decided that we did want to talk to them

207
00:11:55,129 --> 00:11:59,194
and we did want to find a way to hold accountable conversations with them.

208
00:11:59,905 --> 00:12:02,046
We made that decision because we really understand

209
00:12:02,086 --> 00:12:04,067
that this issue of harassment and abuse

210
00:12:04,307 --> 00:12:06,028
is cultural and systemic,

211
00:12:06,889 --> 00:12:09,310
not necessarily because of individual bad apples.

212
00:12:10,010 --> 00:12:12,171
And ultimately, for people to change,

213
00:12:12,251 --> 00:12:13,672
they have to feel supported.

214
00:12:13,732 --> 00:12:17,914
It's really hard to want to make hard changes in yourself

215
00:12:18,054 --> 00:12:20,355
when you feel like there's no hope and no one would care.

216
00:12:21,128 --> 00:12:22,971
But at the same time, it's not always appropriate

217
00:12:22,991 --> 00:12:24,534
for the victim, survivor,

218
00:12:24,654 --> 00:12:26,897
or directly impacted community to offer support.

219
00:12:27,498 --> 00:12:29,882
And we also know that our current institutions

220
00:12:29,942 --> 00:12:32,467
are often more complicit than accountable

221
00:12:32,747 --> 00:12:34,109
and offer very little support

222
00:12:34,149 --> 00:12:35,472
for people who have caused harm as well.

223
00:12:36,423 --> 00:12:40,605
